vectorData.altText: 24. In this image, the tongue has been retracted medially (toward the camera) and inferiorly. Identify A:
That's right!  ’A’ is the hyoglossus muscle. As the name suggests, this extrinsic muscle of the tongue extends from the hyoid bone to the tongue.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.
Medial to the lingual nerve (A), identify the vertically-oriented

fibres of the hyoglossus muscle (B). The hyoglossus muscle, like the genioglossus muscle (C) and styloglossus muscle (D), is an extrinsic muscle of the tongue     . The fibres of the hyoglossus pass superiorly from the hyoid bone (E) to blend with the muscles of the tongue. Inferior to the lingual nerve, identify the hypoglossal nerve (F), running lateral to the hyoglossus. 
The lingual artery (G), a branch of the external carotid artery (H), passes medial to the hyoglossus.

The sublingual gland is innervated by postganglionic parasympathetic fibres under control of the facial nerve.  Preganglionic fibres are carried in the chorda tympani branch of the facial nerve. These fibres join the lingual branch of the mandibular nerve, V3, which carries them into the floor of the mouth, where they synapse on the submandibular ganglion. 
The sublingual salivary glands have about a dozen short ducts that open directly into the floor of the mouth.

always end in “glossus”, which describes their insertion point. The first part of their name describes their bony origin: genioglossus: chin-to-tongue, hyoglossus: hyoid bone to tongue, styloglossus: styloid process to tongue.
